H. monogynum
has been used as a folk Chinese medicine for the treatment of inflammatory related diseases, and COX-2 is a crucial target for the development of agents to treat inflammation. Therefore, we evaluated the in vitro anti-inflammatory properties of compounds 1–16 . The results ( Table 3 ) showed that flavonoids 8–11 showed significant inhibitory activity, with IC 50 values ranging from 0.220 ± 0.006 to 1.655 ± 0.098 μM (
). Among them, flavonoids with substituted sugars ( 8 , 10 , and 11 ) were the best COX-2 inhibitors, with IC 50 values ranging from 0.220 ± 0.006 –0.265 μM. PPAP derivatives ( 1–7 ) and phenolics ( 12–16 ) showed no activity (IC 50 > 20 μM).

To investigate the molecular recognition mechanism between the most active compound and COX-2, compound 8 was applied to in silico analysis with a human COX-2 protein model (PDB code: 5IKQ) (
;
). As shown in Fig. 7 , the results demonstrate that hydrogen bonds exist between 8 and residues in the hydrophobic channel, leading to the catalytic site of the protein. Specifically, five hydrogen bonds were observed to form between a carbonyl group of C-4 and TRP-387, between 4 ′′ -OH and HIS-214, between 6 ′′′ -OH and GLN-289, and between 7 ′′′ -OH and ASC-222. Moreover, the structure of 8 was packed into the hydrophobic pocket formed by GLN-203, LEU-291, TRP-387, and LYS-214, favoring binding. These interactions contribute to the localization of the inhibitor within the hydrophobic COX-2 channel ( Fig. 7 ).

Since many PPAP derivatives have been reported to possess moderate to significant MDR reversal activities (
;
), compounds 1–7 and 9 (20 μM) along with adriamycin (ADR, 40 μM) were evaluated for their MDR reversal activity against MCF-7/ADR cells by the MTT method ( Table 4 ). Then, the active compounds ( 1 , 2 , 6 , and 7 ) were screened for their cytotoxicity against MCF-7/ADR cells, and no obvious cytotoxicity toward the tested cell lines was observed (IC 50 > 150 μM). The results showed that four PPAPs ( 1 , 2 , 6 , and 7 ) showed moderate reversal activity against MCF-7/ADR cells at a concentration of 20 μM, with reverse folds (RFs) ranging from 11 to 27 ( Table 4 ). When compounds 1 and 2 with a unit A fragment were oxidized to a side chain ( 3 ) or an ester ( 4 ) or degraded to a hydrogen atom ( 5 ), the activity disappeared.

In this work, sixteen chemical monomers (
1–16
